## Security & Error Handling Review

### 1. 🔴 Missing `express.json()` / Body Parsing Middleware
If you add POST/PUT routes later (very likely), there's no body parser configured. Without it, `req.body` will be `undefined`, leading to silent failures or unvalidated input.

```js
app.use(express.json({ limit: '10kb' })); // Limit payload size to prevent DoS
app.use(express.urlencoded({ extended: false }));
```

### 2. 🔴 No Rate Limiting
The `/users` endpoint (and any future endpoints) are wide open to brute-force or scraping attacks.

```js
const rateLimit = require('express-rate-limit');
const limiter = rateLimit({ windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, max: 100 });
app.use(limiter);
```

### 3. 🔴 Missing Security Headers
No HTTP security headers are set. Use **Helmet** to add them automatically:

```js
const helmet = require('helmet');
app.use(helmet()); // Sets X-Frame-Options, CSP, HSTS, X-Content-Type-Options, etc.
```

### 4. 🟡 No Global Error Handler
Express has no catch-all error handler, so unhandled errors will leak stack traces or crash silently.

```js
// Add at the end, before module.exports
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(err.stack); // Log internally, never expose to client
  res.status(err.status || 500).json({ error: 'Internal Server Error' });
});
```

### 5. 🟡 No 404 Handler
Unknown routes return Express's default HTML 404, which leaks framework info.

```js
app.use((req, res) => {
  res.status(404).json({ error: 'Not Found' });
});
```

### 6. 🟡 Hardcoded Port with No Fallback
Port `3000` is hardcoded. Use an environment variable with a safe default:

```js
const PORT = parseInt(process.env.PORT, 10) || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`));
